# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gan-networks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:gan-networks/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:gan-networks/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A **generative adversarial network** (**GAN**) is a class of machine learning frameworks and a prominent framework for approaching generative artificial intelligence.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The concept was initially developed by Ian Goodfellow and his colleagues in June 2014.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In a GAN, two neural networks compete with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one agent's gain is another agent's loss.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Given a training set, this technique learns to generate new data with the same statistics as the training set.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, a GAN trained on photographs can generate new photographs that look at least superficially authentic to human observers, having many realistic characteristics.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Though originally proposed as a form of generative model for unsupervised learning, GANs have also proved useful for semi-supervised learning, fully supervised learning, and reinforcement learning.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The core idea of a GAN is based on the "indirect" training through the discriminator, another neural network that can tell how "realistic" the input seems, which itself is also being updated dynamically.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This means that the generator is not trained to minimize the distance to a specific image, but rather to fool the discriminator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This enables the model to learn in an unsupervised manner.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs are similar to mimicry in evolutionary biology, with an evolutionary arms race between both networks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator's task is to approach $\mu _{G}\approx \mu _{\text{ref}}$ , that is, to match its own output distribution as closely as possible to the reference distribution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator's task is to output a value close to 1 when the input appears to be from the reference distribution, and to output a value close to 0 when the input looks like it came from the generator distribution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The *generative* network generates candidates while the *discriminative* network evaluates them.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This creates a contest based on data distributions, where the generator learns to map from a latent space to the true data distribution, aiming to produce candidates that the discriminator cannot distinguish from real data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator's goal is to correctly identify these candidates, but as the generator improves, its task becomes more challenging, increasing the discriminator's error rate.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A known dataset serves as the initial training data for the discriminator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Training involves presenting it with samples from the training dataset until it achieves acceptable accuracy.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator is trained based on whether it succeeds in fooling the discriminator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Typically, the generator is seeded with randomized input that is sampled from a predefined latent space (e.g. a multivariate normal distribution).
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Thereafter, candidates synthesized by the generator are evaluated by the discriminator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Independent backpropagation procedures are applied to both networks so that the generator produces better samples, while the discriminator becomes more skilled at flagging synthetic samples.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When used for image generation, the generator is typically a deconvolutional neural network, and the discriminator is a convolutional neural network.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs are **implicit generative models**, which means that they do not explicitly model the likelihood function nor provide a means for finding the latent variable corresponding to a given sample, unlike alternatives such as flow-based generative model.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Compared to fully visible belief networks such as WaveNet and PixelRNN and autoregressive models in general, GANs can generate one complete sample in one pass, rather than multiple passes through the network.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Compared to Boltzmann machines and linear ICA, there is no restriction on the type of function used by the network.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Since neural networks are universal approximators, GANs are asymptotically consistent.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Variational autoencoders might be universal approximators, but it is not proven as of 2017.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This section provides some of the mathematical theory behind these methods.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In modern probability theory based on measure theory, a probability space also needs to be equipped with a σ-algebra.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Since issues of measurability never arise in practice, these will not concern us further.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the most generic version of the GAN game described above, the strategy set for the discriminator contains all Markov kernels $\mu _{D}:\Omega \to {\mathcal {P}}[0,1]$ , and the strategy set for the generator contains arbitrary probability distributions $\mu _{G}$ on $\Omega$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, as shown below, the optimal discriminator strategy against any $\mu _{G}$ is deterministic, so there is no loss of generality in restricting the discriminator's strategies to deterministic functions $D:\Omega \to [0,1]$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In most applications, D is a deep neural network function.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] As for the generator, while $\mu _{G}$ could theoretically be any computable probability distribution, in practice, it is usually implemented as a pushforward: $\mu _{G}=\mu _{Z}\circ G^{-1}$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] That is, start with a random variable $z\sim \mu _{Z}$ , where $\mu _{Z}$ is a probability distribution that is easy to compute (such as the uniform distribution, or the Gaussian distribution), then define a function $G:\Omega _{Z}\to \Omega$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then the distribution $\mu _{G}$ is the distribution of $G(z)$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Consequently, the generator's strategy is usually defined as just G , leaving $z\sim \mu _{Z}$ implicit.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN architecture has two main components.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One is casting optimization into a game, of form $\min _{G}\max _{D}L(G,D)$ , which is different from the usual kind of optimization, of form $\min _{\theta }L(\theta )$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The other is the decomposition of $\mu _{G}$ into $\mu _{Z}\circ G^{-1}$ , which can be understood as a reparametrization trick.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To see its significance, one must compare GAN with previous methods for learning generative models, which were plagued with "intractable probabilistic computations that arise in maximum likelihood estimation and related strategies".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] At the same time, Kingma and Welling and Rezende et al. developed the same idea of reparametrization into a general stochastic backpropagation method.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Among its first applications was the variational autoencoder.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] If both the generator's and the discriminator's strategy sets are spanned by a finite number of strategies, then by the minimax theorem, $\min _{\mu _{G}}\max _{\mu _{D}}L(\mu _{G},\mu _{D})=\max _{\mu _{D}}\min _{\mu _{G}}L(\mu _{G},\mu _{D})$ that is, the move order does not matter.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, since the strategy sets are both not finitely spanned, the minimax theorem does not apply, and the idea of an "equilibrium" becomes delicate.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For general games, these equilibria do not have to agree, or even to exist.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For the original GAN game, these equilibria all exist, and are all equal.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] However, for more general GAN games, these do not necessarily exist, or agree.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] where the derivative is the Radon–Nikodym derivative, and $D_{JS}$ is the Jensen–Shannon divergence.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The integrand is just the negative cross-entropy between two Bernoulli random variables with parameters $\rho _{\text{ref}}(x)$ and $D(x)$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] That is, the generator perfectly mimics the reference, and the discriminator outputs ${\frac {1}{2}}$ deterministically on all inputs.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] By Jensen's inequality, the discriminator can only improve by adopting the deterministic strategy of always playing $D(x)=\operatorname {E} _{y\sim \mu _{D}(x)}[y]$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When $\forall x\in \Omega ,\mu _{D}(x)=\delta _{\frac {1}{2}}$ , any strategy is optimal for the generator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] While the GAN game has a unique global equilibrium point when both the generator and discriminator have access to their entire strategy sets, the equilibrium is no longer guaranteed when they have a restricted strategy set.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In practice, the generator has access only to measures of form $\mu _{Z}\circ G_{\theta }^{-1}$ , where $G_{\theta }$ is a function computed by a neural network with parameters $\theta$ , and $\mu _{Z}$ is an easily sampled distribution, such as the uniform or normal distribution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Similarly, the discriminator has access only to functions of form $D_{\zeta }$ , a function computed by a neural network with parameters $\zeta$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] These restricted strategy sets take up a *vanishingly small proportion* of their entire strategy sets.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Further, even if an equilibrium still exists, it can only be found by searching in the high-dimensional space of all possible neural network functions.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The standard strategy of using gradient descent to find the equilibrium often does not work for GAN, and often the game "collapses" into one of several failure modes.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To improve the convergence stability, some training strategies start with an easier task, such as generating low-resolution images or simple images (one object with uniform background), and gradually increase the difficulty of the task during training.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This essentially translates to applying a curriculum learning scheme.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs often suffer from **mode collapse** where they fail to generalize properly, missing entire modes from the input data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, a GAN trained on the MNIST dataset containing many samples of each digit might only generate pictures of digit 0.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This was termed "the Helvetica scenario".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A typical mechanism for mode collapse is the generator only generating one or a few of the likely values, or a very incomplete picture of the target distribution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] As the discriminator is only trained to distinguish real from fake samples, it will correctly identify the generated samples as real, but no penalty is imposed on the GAN's ability to generate data that represents the full range of the target distribution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Weak discriminators, for instance underparametrized ones, or ones trained too slow compared to the generator, may as well be unable to fully discriminate over the entire support of the distribution, and only become able to correctly discriminate a very incomplete part of the target distribution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Some researchers perceive the root problem to be a weak discriminative network that fails to notice the pattern of omission, while others assign blame to a bad choice of objective function.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many solutions have been proposed, but it is still an open problem.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Even the state-of-the-art architecture, BigGAN (2019), could not avoid mode collapse.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The authors resorted to "allowing collapse to occur at the later stages of training, by which time a model is sufficiently trained to achieve good results".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The **two time-scale update rule (TTUR)** is proposed to make GAN convergence more stable by making the learning rate of the generator lower than that of the discriminator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They prove that when trained this way, GANs "converge, under mild assumptions to a stationary local Nash equilibrium".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They further show that this property extends to the use of the Adam optimizer, which is commonly used in stochastic gradient descent.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] A local Nash equilibrium in no way signifies an absence of mode collapse - for instance, a GAN trained on MNIST collapsed to generating a single digit may satisfy the hypotheses of the paper, while still presenting mode collapse.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Conversely, if the discriminator learns too fast compared to the generator, then the discriminator could almost perfectly distinguish $\mu _{G_{\theta }},\mu _{\text{ref}}$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such case, the generator $G_{\theta }$ could be stuck with a very high loss no matter which direction it changes its $\theta$ , meaning that the gradient $\nabla _{\theta }L(G_{\theta },D_{\zeta })$ would be close to zero.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such case, the generator cannot learn, a case of the **vanishing gradient** problem.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Intuitively speaking, the discriminator is too good, and since the generator cannot take any small step (only small steps are considered in gradient descent) to improve its payoff, it does not even try.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One important method for solving this problem is the Wasserstein GAN.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many papers that propose new GAN architectures for image generation report how their architectures break the state of the art on FID or IS.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The model is finetuned so that it can approximate $\|f_{\theta }(x)-f_{\theta }(x')\|\approx \operatorname {perceptual~difference} (x,x')$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This finetuned model is then used to define $\operatorname {LPIPS} (x,x'):=\|f_{\theta }(x)-f_{\theta }(x')\|$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Other evaluation methods are reviewed in.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] There is a veritable zoo of GAN variants.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Conditional GANs are similar to standard GANs except they allow the model to conditionally generate samples based on additional information.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, if we want to generate a cat face given a dog picture, we could use a conditional GAN.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The generator in a GAN game generates $\mu _{G}$ , a probability distribution on the probability space $\Omega$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This leads to the idea of a conditional GAN, where instead of generating one probability distribution on $\Omega$ , the generator generates a different probability distribution $\mu _{G}(c)$ on $\Omega$ , for each given class label c .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, for generating images that look like ImageNet, the generator should be able to generate a picture of cat when given the class label "cat".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the original paper, the authors noted that GAN can be trivially extended to conditional GAN by providing the labels to both the generator and the discriminator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In 2017, a conditional GAN learned to generate 1000 image classes of ImageNet.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN game is a general framework and can be run with any reasonable parametrization of the generator G and discriminator D .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In the original paper, the authors demonstrated it using multilayer perceptron networks and convolutional neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many alternative architectures have been tried.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Many GAN variants are merely obtained by changing the loss functions for the generator and discriminator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This objective for generator was recommended in the original paper for faster convergence. $L_{G}=\operatorname {E} _{x\sim \mu _{G}}[\ln D(x)]$ The effect of using this objective is analyzed in Section 2.2.2 of Arjovsky et al.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When the discriminator is optimal, the generator gradient is the same as in maximum likelihood estimation, even though GAN cannot perform maximum likelihood estimation *itself*.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] One of its purposes is to solve the problem of mode collapse (see above).
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The authors claim "In no experiment did we see evidence of mode collapse for the WGAN algorithm".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] An adversarial autoencoder (AAE) is more autoencoder than GAN.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The idea is to start with a plain autoencoder, but train a discriminator to discriminate the latent vectors from a reference distribution (often the normal distribution).
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In conditional GAN, the generator receives both a noise vector z and a label c , and produces an image $G(z,c)$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator receives image-label pairs $(x,c)$ , and computes $D(x,c)$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When the training dataset is unlabeled, conditional GAN does not work directly.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The standard GAN generator is a function of type $G:\Omega _{Z}\to \Omega _{X}$ , that is, it is a mapping from a latent space $\Omega _{Z}$ to the image space $\Omega _{X}$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This can be understood as a "decoding" process, whereby every latent vector $z\in \Omega _{Z}$ is a code for an image $x\in \Omega _{X}$ , and the generator performs the decoding.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This naturally leads to the idea of training another network that performs "encoding", creating an autoencoder out of the encoder-generator pair.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Already in the original paper, the authors noted that "Learned approximate inference can be performed by training an auxiliary network to predict z given x ".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The bidirectional GAN architecture performs exactly this.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Applications of bidirectional models include semi-supervised learning, interpretable machine learning, and neural machine translation.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] CycleGAN is an architecture for performing translations between two domains, such as between photos of horses and photos of zebras, or photos of night cities and photos of day cities.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Unlike previous work like pix2pix, which requires paired training data, cycleGAN requires no paired data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The BigGAN is essentially a self-attention GAN trained on a large scale (up to 80 million parameters) to generate large images of ImageNet (up to 512 x 512 resolution), with numerous engineering tricks to make it converge.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] When there is insufficient training data, the reference distribution $\mu _{\text{ref}}$ cannot be well-approximated by the empirical distribution given by the training dataset.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] In such cases, data augmentation can be applied, to allow training GAN on smaller datasets.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Naïve data augmentation, however, brings its problems.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The result of such training would be a generator that mimics $\mu _{\text{ref}}'$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] For example, it would generate images that look like they are randomly cropped, if the data augmentation uses random cropping.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The StyleGAN-2-ADA paper points out a further point on data augmentation: it must be *invertible*.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Continue with the example of generating ImageNet pictures.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They would have exactly the same expected loss, and so neither is preferred over the other.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The solution is to only use invertible data augmentation: instead of "randomly rotate the picture by 0, 90, 180, 270 degrees with *equal* probability", use "randomly rotate the picture by 90, 180, 270 degrees with 0.1 probability, and keep the picture as it is with 0.7 probability".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This way, the generator is still rewarded to keep images oriented the same way as un-augmented ImageNet pictures.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Abstractly, the effect of randomly sampling transformations $T:\Omega \to \Omega$ from the distribution $\mu _{\text{trans}}$ is to define a Markov kernel $K_{\text{trans}}:\Omega \to {\mathcal {P}}(\Omega )$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then, the data-augmented GAN game pushes the generator to find some ${\hat {\mu }}_{G}\in {\mathcal {P}}(\Omega )$ , such that $K_{\text{trans}}*\mu _{\text{ref}}=K_{\text{trans}}*{\hat {\mu }}_{G}$ where * is the Markov kernel convolution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Also by definition, if the data-augmentation method is invertible, then using it in a GAN game does not change the optimal strategy ${\hat {\mu }}_{G}$ for the generator, which is still $\mu _{\text{ref}}$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] With that, we can recover $\mu$ by running the heat equation *backwards in time* for $\epsilon ^{2}/4$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] More examples of invertible data augmentations are found in the paper.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] SinGAN pushes data augmentation to the limit, by using only a single image as training data and performing data augmentation on it.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The GAN architecture is adapted to this training method by using a multi-scale pipeline.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The discriminator is decomposed into a pyramid as well.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The StyleGAN family is a series of architectures published by Nvidia's research division.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Progressive GAN is a method for training GAN for large-scale image generation stably, by growing a GAN generator from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Like SinGAN, it decomposes the generator as $G=G_{1}\circ G_{2}\circ \cdots \circ G_{N}$ , and the discriminator as $D=D_{1}\circ D_{2}\circ \cdots \circ D_{N}$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] During training, at first only $G_{N},D_{N}$ are used in a GAN game to generate 4x4 images.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then $G_{N-1},D_{N-1}$ are added to reach the second stage of GAN game, to generate 8x8 images, and so on, until we reach a GAN game to generate 1024x1024 images.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To avoid shock between stages of the GAN game, each new layer is "blended in" (Figure 2 of the paper).
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-1 is designed as a combination of Progressive GAN with neural style transfer.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The key architectural choice of StyleGAN-1 is a progressive growth mechanism, similar to Progressive GAN.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Each generated image starts as a constant $4\times 4\times 512$ array, and repeatedly passed through style blocks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Each style block applies a "style latent vector" via affine transform ("adaptive instance normalization"), similar to how neural style transfer uses Gramian matrix.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] It then adds noise, and normalize (subtract the mean, then divide by the variance).
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] After training, multiple style latent vectors can be fed into each style block.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Those fed to the lower layers control the large-scale styles, and those fed to the higher layers control the fine-detail styles.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Style-mixing between two images $x,x'$ can be performed as well.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] First, run a gradient descent to find $z,z'$ such that $G(z)\approx x,G(z')\approx x'$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This is called "projecting an image back to style latent space".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Then, z can be fed to the lower style blocks, and $z'$ to the higher style blocks, to generate a composite image that has the large-scale style of x , and the fine-detail style of $x'$ .
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Multiple images can also be composed this way.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-2 improves upon StyleGAN-1, by using the style latent vector to transform the convolution layer's weights instead, thus solving the "blob" problem.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This was updated by the StyleGAN-2-ADA ("ADA" stands for "adaptive"), which uses invertible data augmentation as described above.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] It also tunes the amount of data augmentation applied by starting at zero, and gradually increasing it until an "overfitting heuristic" reaches a target level, thus the name "adaptive".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] StyleGAN-3 improves upon StyleGAN-2 by solving the "texture sticking" problem, which can be seen in the official videos.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They analyzed the problem by the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, and argued that the layers in the generator learned to exploit the high-frequency signal in the pixels they operate upon.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] To solve this, they proposed imposing strict lowpass filters between each generator's layers, so that the generator is forced to operate on the pixels in a way faithful to the continuous signals they represent, rather than operate on them as merely discrete signals.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] They further imposed rotational and translational invariance by using more signal filters.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The resulting StyleGAN-3 is able to solve the texture sticking problem, as well as generating images that rotate and translate smoothly.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] Other than for generative and discriminative modelling of data, GANs have been used for other things.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] GANs have been used for transfer learning to enforce the alignment of the latent feature space, such as in deep reinforcement learning.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] This works by feeding the embeddings of the source and target task to the discriminator which tries to guess the context.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p01] The resulting loss is then (inversely) backpropagated through the encoder.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN-generated molecules were validated experimentally in mice.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] One of the major concerns in medical imaging is preserving patient privacy.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Due to these reasons, researchers often face difficulties in obtaining medical images for their research purposes.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN has been used for generating synthetic medical images, such as MRI and PET images to address this challenge.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GAN can be used to detect glaucomatous images helping the early diagnosis which is essential to avoid partial or total loss of vision.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs have been used to create forensic facial reconstructions of deceased historical figures.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Concerns have been raised about the potential use of GAN-based human image synthesis for sinister purposes, e.g., to produce fake, possibly incriminating, photographs and videos.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs can be used to generate unique, realistic profile photos of people who do not exist, in order to automate creation of fake social media profiles.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Both bills were authored by Assembly member Marc Berman and signed by Governor Gavin Newsom.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] DARPA's Media Forensics program studies ways to counteract fake media, including fake media produced using GANs.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Some have worked with using GAN for artistic creativity, as "creative adversarial network".
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] A GAN, trained on a set of 15,000 portraits from WikiArt from the 14th to the 19th century, created the 2018 painting *Edmond de Belamy,* which sold for US$432,500.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs were used by the video game modding community to up-scale low-resolution 2D textures in old video games by recreating them in 4k or higher resolutions via image training, and then down-sampling them to fit the game's native resolution (resembling supersampling anti-aliasing).
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2020, Artbreeder was used to create the main antagonist in the sequel to the psychological web horror series *Ben Drowned*.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] The author would later go on to praise GAN applications for their ability to help generate assets for independent artists who are short on budget and manpower.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In May 2020, Nvidia researchers taught an AI system (termed "GameGAN") to recreate the game of *Pac-Man* simply by watching it being played.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In August 2019, a large dataset consisting of 12,197 MIDI songs each with paired lyrics and melody alignment was created for neural melody generation from lyrics using conditional GAN-LSTM (refer to sources at GitHub AI Melody Generation from Lyrics).
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 1991, Juergen Schmidhuber published "artificial curiosity", neural networks in a zero-sum game.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] GANs can be regarded as a case where the environmental reaction is 1 or 0 depending on whether the first network's output is in a given set.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Other people had similar ideas but did not develop them similarly.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] An idea involving adversarial networks was published in a 2010 blog post by Olli Niemitalo.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] This idea was never implemented and did not involve stochasticity in the generator and thus was not a generative model.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] An idea similar to GANs was used to model animal behavior by Wei Li, Melvin Gauci and Roderich Gross in 2013.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Another inspiration for GANs was noise-contrastive estimation, which uses the same loss function as GANs and which Goodfellow studied during his PhD in 2010–2014.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Adversarial machine learning has other uses besides generative modeling and can be applied to models other than neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In control theory, adversarial learning based on neural networks was used in 2006 to train robust controllers in a game theoretic sense, by alternating the iterations between a minimizer policy, the controller, and a maximizer policy, the disturbance.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2017, a GAN was used for image enhancement focusing on realistic textures rather than pixel-accuracy, producing a higher image quality at high magnification.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] In 2017, the first faces were generated.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] These were exhibited in February 2018 at the Grand Palais.
[src:gan-networks/generative-adversarial-network-p02] Faces generated by StyleGAN in 2019 drew comparisons with Deepfakes.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The prevalence of generative AI tools has increased significantly since the AI boom in the 2020s.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] This boom was made possible by improvements in deep neural networks, particularly large language models (LLMs), which are based on the transformer architecture.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI applications include chatbots such as ChatGPT, Claude, Copilot, DeepSeek, Doubao, Google Gemini, Grok and Qwen; text-to-image models such as DALL-E, Firefly, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney; and text-to-video models such as Veo, LTX and Sora.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies in a variety of sectors have used generative AI, including those in software development, healthcare, finance, entertainment, customer service, sales and marketing, art, writing, and product design.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been used for cybercrime, and to deceive and manipulate people through fake news and deepfakes.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models have been trained on copyrighted works without the rightholders' permission.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI systems use large-scale data centers, whose environmental impacts include electronic waste, consumption of fresh water for cooling, and high energy consumption that is estimated to be growing steadily.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The origins of algorithmically generated media can be traced to the development of the Markov chain, which has been used to model natural language since the early 20th century.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Russian mathematician Andrey Markov introduced the concept in 1906, including an analysis of vowel and consonant patterns in *Eugene Onegin*.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Once trained on a text corpus, a Markov chain can generate probabilistic text.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] By the early 1970s, artists began using computers to extend generative techniques beyond Markov models.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Harold Cohen developed and exhibited works produced by AARON, a pioneering computer program designed to autonomously create paintings.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The terms generative AI planning or generative planning were used in the 1980s and 1990s to refer to AI planning systems, especially computer-aided process planning, used to generate sequences of actions to reach a specified goal.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI planning systems used symbolic AI methods such as state space search and constraint satisfaction and were a "relatively mature" technology by the early 1990s.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] They were used to generate crisis action plans for military use, process plans for manufacturing and decision plans such as in prototype autonomous spacecraft.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Machine learning uses both discriminative models and generative models to predict or generate data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Beginning in the late 2000s and early 2010s, advances in deep learning led to major improvements in image classification, speech recognition, and natural language processing.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Neural networks in this period were typically trained as discriminative models due to the relative difficulty of training generative models.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2014, the introduction of models such as the variational autoencoder (VAE) and generative adversarial network (GAN) enabled effective deep generative modeling of complex data such as images.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2017, the Transformer architecture enabled further advances in generative modeling compared to earlier long short-term memory (LSTM) networks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] This led to the development of generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) models, beginning with GPT-1 in 2018.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2020, the release of 15.ai, a free web application created by an anonymous MIT researcher that could generate convincing character voices using minimal training data, was one of the earliest publicly available uses for generative AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The platform is credited as the first mainstream service for audio deepfakes.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2021, DALL-E, a closed-source transformer-based generative model developed by OpenAI, drew widespread attention to text-to-image generation.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other projects, including open-source approaches such as VQGAN+CLIP and DALL·E Mini (later renamed Craiyon), made similar systems more accessible to the public.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Dream by Wombo was released at the end of 2021, followed by the releases of Midjourney and Stable Diffusion in 2022.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In November 2022, ChatGPT was released to the public.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] By 2023, it popularized generative AI for general-purpose text-based tasks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a 2024 survey by marketing research firm Ipsos, Asia–Pacific countries were significantly more optimistic than Western societies about generative AI and show higher adoption rates.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite expressing concerns about privacy and the pace of change, 68% of Asia-Pacific respondents believed that AI was having a positive impact on the world, compared to 57% globally.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a survey by SAS and Coleman Parkes Research, as of 2023, 83% of Chinese respondents were using the technology, exceeding both the global average of 54% and the U.S. rate of 65%.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A UN report indicated that Chinese entities filed over 38,000 generative AI patents from 2014 to 2023, more than any other country.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2024 survey by the Just So Soul social media app reported that 18% of respondents born after 2000 used generative AI "almost every day", and that over 60% of respondents like or love AI-generated content (AIGC), while less than 3% dislike or hate it.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative artificial intelligence has been applied across multiple industries for content creation and automation.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In healthcare, generative models are used for drug discovery and the generation of synthetic medical data to train diagnostic systems.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In finance, they are used for report drafting, data generation, and customer service automation.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Media and entertainment industries use generative systems for tasks such as music composition, script development, and image or video generation.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Researchers and policymakers have raised concerns regarding accuracy, misuse, and impacts on academic and professional work.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Large language models (LLMs) are trained on tokenized text from large corpora and are capable of natural language processing, machine translation, and natural language generation.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] LLMs can be used as foundation models for a variety of downstream tasks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] They can also be trained on source code to generate programs from prompts.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2016, DeepMind's WaveNet demonstrated that deep neural networks can generate raw audio waveforms.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] This enabled more realistic speech synthesis compared to earlier approaches.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Subsequent systems such as Tacotron 2 demonstrated end-to-end neural text-to-speech generation.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to create visual art.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Such systems are trained on image–text pairs.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Examples include Stable Diffusion, DALL-E, and Midjourney.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to produce photorealistic videos.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Systems such as Runway have demonstrated text-to-video generation capabilities.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can be used for motion planning and robot control by learning from prior data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative models can assist in automating 3D modeling tasks, including generating 3D assets from text or images.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] World models are neural networks designed to learn representations of physical environments, including spatial and dynamic properties.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Recent multimodal systems have expanded these capabilities by integrating vision, language, and action into unified models.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems have been used in mathematics and computer science to generate candidate computer programs, proofs, constructions, or algorithms.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced FunSearch, a method for creating computer programs that solve mathematical and algorithmic problems.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] FunSearch was used to discover new mathematical constructions in the cap set problem and the bin packing problem.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaDev, which was used to discover small sorting algorithms that outperformed previously known human benchmarks and have been integrated into the LLVM standard C++ sorting library.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Google DeepMind introduced AlphaEvolve, an AI system for general-purpose algorithm discovery and optimization.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] AlphaEvolve uses LLMs to propose code changes, automated evaluators to assess each candidate, and an evolutionary process to iteratively improve algorithms.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, Google DeepMind introduced GNoME, a method to propose candidate inorganic crystal structures for computational screening and experimental synthesis in material science.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Other material science methods include MatterGen, CDVAE, and CrystalFlow.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative engine optimization (GEO) is the practice of structuring digital content and managing online presence to improve visibility in responses generated by generative AI systems.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The practice influences the way large language models (LLMs) retrieve, summarize, and present information in response to user queries.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Related terms include answer engine optimization (AEO) and artificial intelligence optimization (AIO).
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI models are used to power chatbot products such as ChatGPT, programming tools such as GitHub Copilot, text-to-image products such as Midjourney, and text-to-video products such as Runway Gen-2.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI features have been integrated into a variety of existing commercially available products such as Microsoft Office (Microsoft Copilot), Google Photos, and the Adobe Suite (Adobe Firefly).
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many generative AI models are also available as open-source software, including Stable Diffusion and the LLaMA language model.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller generative AI models with up to a few billion parameters can run on smartphones, embedded devices, and personal computers.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, LLaMA-7B (a version with 7 billion parameters) can run on a Raspberry Pi 4 and one version of Stable Diffusion can run on an iPhone 11.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Larger models with tens of billions of parameters can run on laptop or desktop computers.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] To achieve an acceptable speed, models of this size may require accelerators such as the GPU chips produced by NVIDIA and AMD or the Neural Engine included in Apple silicon products.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, the 65 billion parameter version of LLaMA can be configured to run on a desktop PC.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The advantages of running generative AI locally include protection of privacy and intellectual property, and avoidance of rate limiting and censorship.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The subreddit r/LocalLLaMA in particular focuses on using consumer-grade gaming graphics cards through such techniques as compression.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Language models with hundreds of billions of parameters, such as GPT-4 or PaLM, typically run on datacenter computers equipped with arrays of GPUs (such as NVIDIA's H100) or AI accelerator chips (such as Google's TPU).
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] These very large models are typically accessed as cloud services over the Internet.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2022, the United States New Export Controls on Advanced Computing and Semiconductors to China imposed restrictions on exports to China of GPU and AI accelerator chips used for generative AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Chips such as the NVIDIA A800 and the Biren Technology BR104 were developed to meet the requirements of the sanctions.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is free software on the market capable of recognizing text generated by generative artificial intelligence (such as GPTZero), as well as images, audio or video coming from it.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Potential mitigation strategies for detecting generative AI content include digital watermarking, content authentication, information retrieval, and machine learning classifier models.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Despite claims of accuracy, both free and paid AI text detectors have frequently produced false positives, mistakenly accusing students of submitting AI-generated work.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) are a generative modeling technique which consist of two neural networks—the generator and the discriminator—trained simultaneously in a competitive setting.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The generator creates synthetic data by transforming random noise into samples that resemble the training dataset.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The discriminator is trained to distinguish the authentic data from synthetic data produced by the generator.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The two models engage in a minimax game: the generator aims to create increasingly realistic data to "fool" the discriminator, while the discriminator improves its ability to distinguish real from fake data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] This continuous training setup enables the generator to produce high-quality and realistic outputs.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Variational autoencoders (VAEs) are deep learning models that probabilistically encode data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] They are typically used for tasks such as noise reduction from images, data compression, identifying unusual patterns, and facial recognition.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike standard autoencoders, which compress input data into a fixed latent representation, VAEs model the latent space as a probability distribution, allowing for smooth sampling and interpolation between data points.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The encoder ("recognition model") maps input data to a latent space, producing means and variances that define a probability distribution.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The decoder ("generative model") samples from this latent distribution and attempts to reconstruct the original input.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Transformers became the foundation for the generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) series developed by OpenAI, replacing traditional recurrent and convolutional models.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The self-attention mechanism enables the model to determine the relative importance of each token in a sequence when predicting the next token, thereby improving contextual understanding.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Unlike recurrent neural networks, transformers process tokens in parallel, which improves training efficiency and scalability.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the United States, a group of companies including OpenAI, Alphabet, and Meta signed a voluntary agreement with the Biden administration in July 2023 to watermark AI-generated content.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In October 2023, Executive Order 14110 applied the Defense Production Act to require all US companies to report information to the federal government when training certain high-impact AI models.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the European Union (EU), the Artificial Intelligence Act includes requirements to disclose copyrighted material used to train generative AI systems, and to label any AI-generated output as such.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In China, the Interim Measures for the Management of Generative AI Services introduced by the Cyberspace Administration of China regulates any public-facing generative AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] It includes requirements to watermark generated images or videos, regulations on training data and label quality, restrictions on personal data collection, and a guideline that generative AI services must "adhere to socialist core values".
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI systems such as ChatGPT and Midjourney are trained on large, publicly available datasets that include copyrighted works.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI developers have argued that such training is protected under fair use, while copyright holders have argued that it infringes their rights.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Proponents of fair use training have argued that it is a transformative use and does not involve making copies of copyrighted works available to the public.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Critics have argued that image generators such as Midjourney can create nearly-identical copies of some copyrighted images, and that generative AI programs compete with the content they are trained on.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] As of 2024, several lawsuits related to the use of copyrighted material in training are ongoing.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Getty Images has sued Stability AI over the use of its images to train Stable Diffusion.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Both the Authors Guild and The New York Times have sued Microsoft and OpenAI over the use of their works to train ChatGPT.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A separate question is whether AI-generated works can qualify for copyright protection.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The United States Copyright Office has ruled that works created by artificial intelligence without any human input cannot be copyrighted, because they lack human authorship.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Some legal professionals have suggested that *Naruto v.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] 9th Circuit Court of Appeals held that non-humans cannot be copyright holders of artistic works, could be a potential precedent in copyright litigation over works created by generative AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the office has also begun taking public input to determine if these rules need to be refined for generative AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Whether such modifications rise to the minimum standard of originality required under Feist will depend on a case-by-case determination.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In those cases where they do, the output should be copyrightable" Subsequently, the USCO registered the first visual artwork to be composed of entirely AI-generated materials, titled "A Single Piece of American Cheese".
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The development of generative AI has raised concerns from governments, businesses, and individuals, resulting in protests, legal actions, calls to pause AI experiments, and actions by multiple governments.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In addition, generative AI has a significant carbon footprint.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study presented in the 2026 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems found that overreliance on generative AI can decrease one's ability to discern misinformation, the study tracked participants, mostly from the UK and US, for a period of 4 weeks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI can be used to generate and modify academic prose, paraphrase sources, and translate languages.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The use of generative AI in a classroom setting has challenged traditional definitions of academic plagiarism, leading to a "cat-and-mouse" dynamic between students using AI and institutions attempting to detect it.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In the immediate wake of ChatGPT's release, many school districts and universities issued temporary bans on the technology, though many institutions have since moved toward policies of managed integration.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, the implementation of these policies often lacks clarity.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Research suggests that the burden of interpreting "acceptable use" frequently falls on individual students and teachers, creating an environment where academic honesty becomes difficult to define and enforce.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A commonly proposed use for teachers is grading and giving feedback.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies like Pearson and ETS use AI to score grammar, mechanics, usage, and style, but not for main ideas or overall structure.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The National Council of Teachers of English stated that machine scoring makes students feel their writing is not worth reading.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI scoring has also given unfair results for students from different ethnic backgrounds.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, it was reported that image generation AI has resulted in 70% of the jobs for video game illustrators in China being lost.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In July 2023, developments in generative AI contributed to the 2023 Hollywood labor disputes.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Fran Drescher, president of the Screen Actors Guild, declared that "artificial intelligence poses an existential threat to creative professions" during the 2023 SAG-AFTRA strike.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Voice generation AI has been seen as a potential challenge to the voice acting sector.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, a 2025 study concluded that the US labor market had so far not experienced a discernible disruption from generative AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Another study reported that Danish workers who used chatbots saved 2.8% of their time on average, and found no significant change in earnings or hours worked.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In January 2023, *Futurism* broke the story that CNET had been using an undisclosed internal AI tool to write at least 77 of its stories; after the news broke, CNET posted corrections to 41 of the stories.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In April 2023, *Die Aktuelle* published an AI-generated fake interview of Michael Schumacher.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2024, *Futurism* noted that a content management system video by AdVon Commerce, which had used generative AI to produce articles for many of the aforementioned outlets, appeared to show that they "had produced tens of thousands of articles for more than 150 publishers".
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, a report from the American Sunlight Project stated that Pravda network was publishing as many as 10,000 articles a day, and concluded that much of this content aimed to push Russian narratives into large language models through their training data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2024, Reuters Institute published its *Digital News Report for 2024*.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In a survey of people in America and Europe, Reuters Institute reports that 52% and 47% respectively are uncomfortable with news produced by "mostly AI with some human oversight", and 23% and 15% respectively report being comfortable.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] 42% of Americans and 33% of Europeans reported that they were comfortable with news produced by "mainly human with some help from AI".
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The results of global surveys reported that people were more uncomfortable with news topics including politics (46%), crime (43%), and local news (37%) produced by AI than other news topics.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2025 Pew Research Survey found roughly half of all U.S. adults say that AI will have a very (24%) or somewhat (26%) negative impact on the news people get in the U.S. over the next 20 years.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A language model may associate certain professions with specific genders if such patterns are prevalent in the data.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similarly, image generation systems prompted with terms such as "a photo of a CEO" have been observed to disproportionately generate images of white male individuals when trained on biased datasets.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI software, when using voice recognition software in particular, struggles to recognize and understand speech impediments.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] For example, people with a stutter struggle to activate voice-activated assistants such as Gemini and Siri due to how the software was trained.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Companies that use AI systems to hire for new positions also filter out people with accents and speech due to voice recognition software incorrectly transcribing how candidates speak during the interview process.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Because of this, people with disabilities and uncommon accents don't often make it to a human interviewer when these generative AI systems are used.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] This is due to many AI models being trained and produced in the United States, and therefore, off of American accents.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes (a portmanteau of "deep learning" and "fake") are AI-generated media that take a person in an existing image or video and replace them with someone else's likeness using artificial neural networks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfakes have garnered widespread attention and concerns for their uses in deepfake celebrity pornographic videos, revenge porn, fake news, hoaxes, health disinformation, financial fraud, and covert foreign election interference.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Instances of users abusing software to generate controversial statements in the vocal style of celebrities, public officials, and other famous individuals have raised ethical concerns over voice generation AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In response, companies such as ElevenLabs have stated that they would work on mitigating potential abuse through safeguards and identity verification.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Concerns and fandoms have spawned from AI-generated music.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The same software used to clone voices has been used on famous musicians' voices to create songs that mimic their voices, gaining both tremendous popularity and criticism.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Similar techniques have also been used to create improved quality or full-length versions of songs that have been leaked or have yet to be released.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI has been noted for its use by state-sponsored propaganda campaigns in information laundering.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to a 2025 report by Graphika, generative AI is used to launder articles from Chinese state media such as China Global Television Network through various social media sites in an attempt to disguise the articles' origin.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A paper published by researchers at Amazon Web Services AI Labs found that over 57% of sentences from a sample of over 6 billion sentences from Common Crawl, a snapshot of web pages, were machine translated.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many of these automated translations were seen as lower quality, especially for sentences that were translated into at least three languages.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Wolof, Xhosa) were translated across more languages than higher-resource languages (ex.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The adoption of generative AI tools led to an explosion of AI-generated content across multiple domains.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A study from University College London estimated that in 2023, more than 60,000 scholarly articles—over 1% of all publications—were likely written with LLM assistance.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] According to Stanford University's Institute for Human-Centered AI, approximately 17.5% of newly published computer science papers and 16.9% of peer review text now incorporate content generated by LLMs.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] If AI-generated content is included in new data crawls from the Internet for additional training of AI models, defects in the resulting models may occur.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training an AI model exclusively on the output of another AI model produces a lower-quality model.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Repeating this process, where each new model is trained on the previous model's output, leads to progressive degradation and eventually results in a "model collapse" after multiple iterations.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] On the other side, synthetic data can be deployed to train machine learning models while preserving user privacy.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The approach is not limited to text generation; image generation has been employed to train computer vision models.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Many websites that allow explicit AI generated images or videos have been created, and this has been used to create illegal content, such as rape, child sexual abuse material, necrophilia, and zoophilia.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Generative AI's ability to create realistic fake content has been exploited in numerous types of cybercrime, including phishing scams.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Deepfake video and audio have been used to create disinformation and fraud.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2020, former Google click fraud czar Shuman Ghosemajumder argued that once deepfake videos become perfectly realistic, they would stop appearing remarkable to viewers, potentially leading to uncritical acceptance of false information.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, large language models and other forms of text-generation AI have been used to create fake reviews of e-commerce websites to boost ratings.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Cybercriminals have created large language models focused on fraud, including WormGPT and FraudGPT.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] A 2023 study showed that generative AI can be vulnerable to jailbreaks, reverse psychology and prompt injection attacks, enabling attackers to obtain help with harmful requests, such as for crafting social engineering and phishing attacks.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Additionally, other researchers have demonstrated that open-source models can be fine-tuned to remove their safety restrictions at low cost.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2025, Israel signed a $6 million contract with the US-based firm Clock Tower X that aimed to influence ChatGPT, Gemini and Grok by spreading pro-Israel information onto social media and websites.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] This was in an attempt to take advantage of the retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) technique which is used by LLMs to provide more up-to-date information.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from covered service providers, including some AI service providers, regardless of where the data is physically stored.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Courts can require parent companies to provide data held by their subsidiaries, and such orders may be accompanied by nondisclosure requirements preventing the provider from notifying affected users.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] This framework has been described in legal commentary as creating legal tension with Article 48 of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] As a result, service providers operating in both jurisdictions may face competing legal obligations under U.S. and EU law.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] AI has a significant carbon footprint due to growing energy consumption from both training and usage.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] There is also concern that these impacts may increase as these models are incorporated into widely used search engines such as Google Search and Bing, as chatbots and other applications become more popular, and as models need to be retrained.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Training frontier AI models requires an enormous amount of computing power.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Usually only Big Tech companies have the financial resources to make such investments.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Smaller start-ups such as Cohere and OpenAI end up buying access to data centers from Google and Microsoft respectively.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Tools such as GPTZero can detect content generated by AI.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] However, they can also make false accusations (false positives).
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] Digital watermarking is a technique that improves detection accuracy.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] It works by altering the generated content at the source, in subtle ways which can be detected by corresponding software.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In 2023, OpenAI developed a watermarking tool for ChatGPT.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] They didn't release it, because they worried that users would switch to competitors.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] They also argued that it would be easy to circumvent, for example by asking another AI to rephrase.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In March 2025, the Cyberspace Administration of China issued rules, requiring online service providers to label AI content.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In May 2025, Google deployed its watermarking tool, SynthID.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] It marks output from Gemini (text), Imagen (images), and Veo (video).
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] To detect output from these products, one uses Google's "SynthID detector" portal.
[src:gan-networks/generative-artificial-intelligence] In June 2025, users mistakenly accused gaming companies of using generative AI for the video games *Little Droid* and *Catly*.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] A **latent space**, also known as a **latent feature space** or **embedding space**, is an embedding of a set of items within a manifold in which items resembling each other are positioned closer to one another.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Position within the latent space can be viewed as being defined by a set of latent variables that emerge from the resemblances between the objects.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] In most cases, the dimensionality of the latent space is chosen to be lower than the dimensionality of the feature space from which the data points are drawn, making the construction of a latent space an example of dimensionality reduction, which can also be viewed as a form of data compression.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Latent spaces are usually fit via machine learning, and they can then be used as feature spaces in machine learning models, including classifiers and other supervised predictors.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] The interpretation of latent spaces in machine learning models is an ongoing area of research, but achieving clear interpretations remains challenging.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] The black-box nature of these models often makes the latent space unintuitive, while its high-dimensional, complex, and nonlinear characteristics further complicate the task of understanding it.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Analysis of the latent space geometry of diffusion models reveals a fractal structure of phase transitions in the latent space, characterized by abrupt changes in the Fisher information metric.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Some visualization techniques have been developed to connect the latent space to the visual world, but there is often not a direct connection between the latent space interpretation and the model itself.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Such techniques include t-distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE), where the latent space is mapped to two dimensions for visualization.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Latent space distances lack physical units, so the interpretation of these distances may depend on the application.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Several embedding models have been developed to perform this transformation to create latent space embeddings given a set of data items and a similarity function.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] These models learn the embeddings by leveraging statistical techniques and machine learning algorithms.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] GloVe: GloVe (Global Vectors for Word Representation) is another widely used embedding model for NLP.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] It combines global statistical information from a corpus with local context information to learn word embeddings.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] GloVe embeddings are known for capturing both semantic and relational similarities between words.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Siamese Networks: Siamese networks are a type of neural network architecture commonly used for similarity-based embedding.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] They consist of two identical subnetworks that process two input samples and produce their respective embeddings.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Siamese networks are often used for tasks like image similarity, recommendation systems, and face recognition.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Variational Autoencoders (VAEs): VAEs are generative models that simultaneously learn to encode and decode data.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] The latent space in VAEs acts as an embedding space.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] By training VAEs on high-dimensional data, such as images or audio, the model learns to encode the data into a compact latent representation.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] VAEs are known for their ability to generate new data samples from the learned latent space.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Multimodality refers to the integration and analysis of multiple modes or types of data within a single model or framework.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Embedding multimodal data involves capturing relationships and interactions between different data types, such as images, text, audio, and structured data.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] Multimodal embedding models aim to learn joint representations that fuse information from multiple modalities, allowing for cross-modal analysis and tasks.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] These models enable applications like image captioning, visual question answering, and multimodal sentiment analysis.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] To embed multimodal data, specialized architectures such as deep multimodal networks or multimodal transformers are employed.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] These architectures combine different types of neural network modules to process and integrate information from various modalities.
[src:gan-networks/latent-space] The resulting embeddings capture the complex relationships between different data types, facilitating multimodal analysis and understanding.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Conceptually, unsupervised learning divides into the aspects of data, training, algorithm, and downstream applications.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Typically, the dataset is harvested cheaply "in the wild", such as massive text corpus obtained by web crawling, with only minor filtering (such as Common Crawl).
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] This compares favorably to supervised learning, where the dataset (such as the ImageNet1000) is typically constructed manually, which is much more expensive.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] There are algorithms designed specifically for unsupervised learning, such as clustering algorithms like k-means, dimensionality reduction techniques like principal component analysis (PCA), Boltzmann machine learning, and autoencoders.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] After the rise of deep learning, most large-scale unsupervised learning has been done by training general-purpose neural network architectures by gradient descent, adapted to performing unsupervised learning by designing an appropriate training procedure.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Sometimes a trained model can be used as-is, but more often they are modified for downstream applications.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] For example, the generative pretraining method trains a model to generate a textual dataset, before finetuning it for other applications, such as text classification.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] As another example, autoencoders are trained to produce good features, which can then be used as a module for other models, such as in a latent diffusion model.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Tasks are often categorized as discriminative (recognition) or generative (imagination).
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Often but not always, discriminative tasks use supervised methods and generative tasks use unsupervised (see Venn diagram); however, the separation is very hazy.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] For example, object recognition favors supervised learning but unsupervised learning can also cluster objects into groups.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Furthermore, as progress marches onward, some tasks employ both methods, and some tasks swing from one to another.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] For example, image recognition started off as heavily supervised, but became hybrid by employing unsupervised pre-training, and then moved towards supervision again with the advent of dropout, ReLU, and adaptive learning rates.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] A typical generative task is as follows.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] At each step, a datapoint is sampled from the dataset, and part of the data is removed, and the model must infer the removed part.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] This is particularly clear for the denoising autoencoders and BERT.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] During the learning phase, an unsupervised network tries to mimic the data it is given and uses the error in its mimicked output to correct itself (i.e. correct its weights and biases).
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Sometimes the error is expressed as a low probability that the erroneous output occurs, or it might be expressed as an unstable high energy state in the network.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] An energy function is a macroscopic measure of a network's activation state.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] In Boltzmann machines, it plays the role of the Cost function.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] This analogy with physics is inspired by Ludwig Boltzmann's analysis of a gas' macroscopic energy from the microscopic probabilities of particle motion $p\propto e^{-E/kT}$ , where k is the Boltzmann constant and T is temperature.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] In the RBM network the relation is $p=e^{-E}/Z$ , where p and E vary over every possible activation pattern and $\textstyle {Z=\sum _{\scriptscriptstyle {\text{All Patterns}}}e^{-E({\text{pattern}})}}$ .
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] To be more precise, $p(a)=e^{-E(a)}/Z$ , where a is an activation pattern of all neurons (visible and hidden).
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Hence, some early neural networks bear the name Boltzmann Machine.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] Paul Smolensky calls $-E\,$ the *Harmony*.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] A network seeks low energy which is high Harmony.
[src:gan-networks/unsupervised-learning] This table shows connection diagrams of various unsupervised networks, the details of which will be given in the section Comparison of Networks.
